SIMPLE: mischief
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mischief
<hw>Mis"chief</hw> <pr>(m⟦icr⟧s"ch⟦icr⟧f)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>meschef</ets> bad result, OF. <ets>meschief</ets>; pref.
<ets>mes-</ets> (L. <ets>minus</ets> less) + <ets>chief</ets> end, head,
F. <ets>chef</ets> chief. See <er>Minus</er>, and
<er>Chief</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Harm; damage; esp., disarrangement of order; trouble
or vexation caused by human agency or by some living being,
intentionally or not; often, calamity, mishap; trivial evil caused by
thoughtlessness, or in sport.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy tongue deviseth <qex>mischiefs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ps. lii.
2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The practice whereof shall, I hope, secure me from many
<qex>mischiefs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Cause of trouble or vexation; trouble.</def>
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>mischief</qex> was, these allies would never allow that
the common enemy was subdued.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To be in mischief</b></col>, <cd>to be doing harm or
causing annoyance.</cd> -- <col><b>To make mischief</b></col>, <cd>to do
mischief, especially by exciting quarrels.</cd> -- <col><b>To play the
mischief</b></col>, <cd>to cause great harm; to throw into
confusion.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Damage; harm; hurt; injury; detriment; evil;
ill.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Mischief</er>, <er>Damage</er>, <er>Harm</er>.
<xex>Damage</xex> is an injury which diminishes the value of a thing;
<xex>harm</xex> is an injury which causes trouble or inconvenience;
<xex>mischief</xex> is an injury which disturbs the order and
consistency of things. We often suffer <xex>damage</xex> or
<xex>harm</xex> from accident, but <xex>mischief</xex> always springs
from perversity or folly.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischief</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mischief
<hw>Mis"chief</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To do harm to.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mischiefable</ent>⟦br⟧
